00:05:08.030 --> 00:05:09.750
Okay. Great.

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:11.050
That's wonderful.

00:05:11.050 --> 00:05:12.520
Thank you.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:16.830
Where my line of work, I'm
inundated with stories all day,

00:05:16.830 --> 00:05:19.190
every day, and I love it.

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:22.880
I believe passionately in the power
that stories and storytelling have

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:26.270
to bring peace, tolerance, and
understanding to our world.

00:05:26.270 --> 00:05:28.520
I believe that we are
all storytellers

00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:31.180
because we are the stories
of those that came after us,

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:33.310
those that came before us.

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:36.710
And as we all learn to listen,
collaborate, and engage,

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:40.310
and share our stories with each
other, all of us have the ability

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:42.870
to write our own storied script.

00:05:42.870 --> 00:05:46.340
All of us in this room
are carriers of stories.

00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:47.640
Stories are part of our DNA.

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:52.580 position:56%
We are all storytellers, hot-blooded
believers in the promises

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.690
of what storytelling can bring.

00:05:54.690 --> 00:05:58.720
We are dreamers, disciples of
tradition, past and present.

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:00.400
We are artists, poets,

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:02.870
administrators, curators,
and citizens.

00:06:02.870 --> 00:06:05.230
Or like me, a H1B resident
alien [laughter].

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:08.650
But regardless of who we
are or where we come from,

00:06:08.650 --> 00:06:10.870
we are all advocates of culture.

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:13.060
My name is Kiran Singh,
and I'm the president

00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:14.920
of the International
Storytelling Center based

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:16.730
in Jonesborough, Tennessee.

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:19.360
But as you can probably
tell by my accent,

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:21.470
I'm not originally from Tennessee.

00:06:21.470 --> 00:06:24.790
I am, in fact, a newly
adopted Tennessean and before

00:06:24.790 --> 00:06:27.610
that a Rotary Peace Fellow
based in North Carolina.

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:30.820
Before that an adopted new Scott
that made, lived and worked,

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:32.140
and made Scotland my home.

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:34.880
And before that an English-born
Sikh of British-Asian,

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:36.710
Indian, and African descent.

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:41.460
Descended from Kampala and Tororo
in Uganda, in Mombasa, Kenya,

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:46.340
and the villages of [foreign
words] in Punjab in northern India.

00:06:46.340 --> 00:06:50.080
Now if you're confused
try celebrating Christmas,

00:06:50.080 --> 00:06:53.050
[foreign words] or Dewali
at my house [laughter].

00:06:53.050 --> 00:06:57.100
I have been with the International
Storytelling Center since 2013,

00:06:57.100 --> 00:07:01.180
but my organization's work
began just over 40 years ago,

00:07:01.180 --> 00:07:05.060
when a local high school teacher
called Jimmy Neil Smith decided he

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:06.940 position:56%
wanted to save a dying mountain town

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:09.160
by creating an annual
storytelling event

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:11.600
that he boldly called the
National Storytelling Festival.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:14.430
Now that was a pretty
fancy name for something

00:07:14.430 --> 00:07:16.630
that was literally 60 people
gathered around a wagon.

00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:20.460
The stages were hay bales,
if you can believe it.

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:23.070
But there was enough magic
there to spark a movement

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:27.770
and something my predecessor likes
to call a storytelling revolution.

00:07:27.770 --> 00:07:29.200
Storytelling revolution.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:31.800
It kind of has a ring
to it, doesn't it?

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:35.000 position:56%
Well around the same time there were
less quaint revolutions happening

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.300
in other parts of the world.

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:38.560
And one of them involved
my own family.

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:42.800
They lived in Uganda at the
time and in the summer of 1972,

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:45.450
one year before the first
festival in Jonesborough

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:48.260
and four years before I was
born, there was an announcement

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:51.760
on Ugandan public radio
by then dictator Idi Amin.

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:54.760
And he declared that all
Ugandan Asians had three months

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:57.530
to leave the country or
they'll all be executed.

00:07:57.530 --> 00:08:01.360
Now that meant around 50,000
people, including my family,

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:03.770
had three months to
flee the country.

00:08:03.770 --> 00:08:05.460
Many fled the borders.

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:07.720
My family left for Britain.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:10.160
They couldn't carry much but
what they could carry was taken

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:13.320
by robbers en route to the airport.

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:16.730
But having left behind all their
possessions and the tropical heat

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:20.280 position:56%
of East Africa, they arrived in a
small English town called Eastbourne

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:24.260
in the middle of a British winter,
and that was where I was born.

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:27.380
As Ugandan refugees,
my parents stood out.

00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:30.430
My father wore a bright red turban
and a colorful African shirt

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:32.760
and my mother an even
brighter red sari.

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:35.670
Later my dad told me about
overhearing a kid tell her mum,

00:08:35.670 --> 00:08:38.240
after seeing my dad,
look mum, aliens.

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:40.210
Meaning aliens from outer space.

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:42.400
And my dad still loves
to tell that story.

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:45.420
Now for the most part,
the vast majority

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:48.720
of people were incredibly kind
and welcoming to my family.

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:51.390
But there were some that
were not so welcoming.

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:54.630
There was racism, and it
existed in my small community.

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:57.670
But as a kid that's not
how you think of it.

00:08:57.670 --> 00:09:01.410
I just knew it was hard to
understand why I felt so different.

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:04.560
Home was always a safe and
familiar space but whenever I had

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:08.770
to leave the house, I felt like I
had to be constantly on my guard.

00:09:08.770 --> 00:09:12.010
It was hard to concentrate at
school, and sometimes I ended

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:13.960
up causing trouble myself.

00:09:13.960 --> 00:09:16.820
But things started to change
for me when my head teacher,

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:20.320
in a weekly school assembly,
started to tell stories.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:22.490
Mr George was an older gentleman.

00:09:22.490 --> 00:09:25.490
He was white, pretty much
like everyone else around me.

00:09:25.490 --> 00:09:29.710
He wore this tweed jacket and a
kind face, and he told us folktales

00:09:29.710 --> 00:09:31.960
and traditional stories
from all over the world,

00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:34.200
and one of them really spoke to me.

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:38.710
It was about a prince who gives
up his worldly riches and goes

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:40.440
out into the world
to explore the world,

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:41.900
and he takes two objects with him.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:44.490
A cup and a toothbrush.

00:09:44.490 --> 00:09:47.450
One day, he looks out and sees
a man break a twig from a tree

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:50.340
and chewing it to release these
juices that would clean his teeth.

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:52.970
And he realized he didn't
need his toothbrush anymore,

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.180
so he threw it away.

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:58.490
Another day he sees
someone bent down by a river

00:09:58.490 --> 00:10:00.040
and cupping their hands
together in the shape

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:02.460
of a bowl to drink the water.

00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:04.490
So he threw his cup away as well,

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:06.850
realizing he didn't
need that either.

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:10.870
Listening to that story, I began to
observe a world in a different way.

00:10:10.870 --> 00:10:13.240
Not only did that story
help to paint a picture

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:16.520
of a world beyond what I already
knew or understood around me,

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:18.200
but it connected me to the idea

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:19.990
that perhaps the world
provides all the things

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:21.970
that we need to live in it.

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:24.450
That story turned my fear to hope.

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:25.960
And it helped me see
the possibilities,

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:27.820
where before I'd seen
the challenges.

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:30.920
It helped me see my own
family's difficult situation --

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:34.030
the idea that parents were
showing up in an unfamiliar country

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:38.040
with just nothing but the clothes
on their back -- in a new way.

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:41.090
They didn't need material
things to connect to new people

00:10:41.090 --> 00:10:43.790
or have new experiences or
to remember the old ones.

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:46.260
And I began to understand
myself, the world,

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:47.670
and my place in the world.

00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:51.160
And I started to see the outlines
of the story that I wanted to see

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:53.990
in the world and how I
can make that happen.

00:10:53.990 --> 00:10:55.430
Hearing that folktale, it felt

00:10:55.430 --> 00:10:57.860
like Mr George was
speaking directly to me.

00:10:57.860 --> 00:11:00.800
And I expect other students, in
totally different situations,

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:05.250
felt the same way, but that's
the magic of a good story.

00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:07.480
For me, these first stories
allowed me to grapple

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:10.930
with challenges then
and for what lay ahead.

00:11:10.930 --> 00:11:13.830
Through story I learnt to
channel anger, frustration,

00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:17.940
and anxiety into injustice
[inaudible] and inequality,

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:21.500
into forms of storied spoken
word and as a slam artist.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:23.430
Because story is my tool.

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:27.060
Telling is my shield, my sword, my
passion, my inspiration to write,

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:30.530
to repeat, to shape, to
understand what I've heard.

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:33.950
When we look beyond divisions and
labels in the societies we live in.

00:11:33.950 --> 00:11:36.590
When we think beyond borders
and groups and allow ourselves

00:11:36.590 --> 00:11:38.250
to embrace the wider world.

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:40.550
We become international
citizens of the world.

00:11:40.550 --> 00:11:45.410
And we start to refigure and
reshape our stories with others.

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:48.950
When I first thought it out
in museums, back in 2001,

00:11:48.950 --> 00:11:50.480
I met an education specialist.

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.790
I gave a talk at the
museum I worked in.

00:11:52.790 --> 00:11:54.750
At the National Museum of Scotland.

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:58.890
And he said the best way to connect
culture to the people was to break

00:11:58.890 --> 00:12:00.860
down the walls of the museum.

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:03.580
Let material culture be free,
he said, and let people come

00:12:03.580 --> 00:12:06.040
and take what rightfully
belongs to them.

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:08.020
Now the idea resonated with me

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:09.930
because here I was a
professional working

00:12:09.930 --> 00:12:12.210
in a major British
cultural institution.

00:12:12.210 --> 00:12:16.130
We had objects, thousands of
them, many contested objects

00:12:16.130 --> 00:12:19.650
that could be argued as stolen,
looted, or acquired illegally.

00:12:19.650 --> 00:12:22.960
If the British Museum were to give
back all of its objects like that,

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:25.710
it would actually lose
10% of its collections.

00:12:25.710 --> 00:12:29.800
But this was my first job in
a museum, my role as a curator

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:32.390
of education was to help
present Scotland to the world

00:12:32.390 --> 00:12:33.880
and the world to Scotland.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:36.400
But to be honest, what
I was finding was

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:39.760
that many British museums often
conveyed imperial perspectives

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:41.300
on British history.

00:12:41.300 --> 00:12:44.660
One such example was an
exhibition called Teas and Tigers

00:12:44.660 --> 00:12:46.970 position:56%
at the National Library of Scotland.

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:50.250
Reading the intro panel, it
described the largest uprising

00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:53.130
against British rule
as the Indian Mutiny.

00:12:53.130 --> 00:12:57.480
As a person of color and
also a part of an empire,

00:12:57.480 --> 00:12:59.690
what was my position
on these issues?

00:12:59.690 --> 00:13:01.470
Whose side was I really on?

00:13:01.470 --> 00:13:03.740
And whose story do I help to tell?

00:13:03.740 --> 00:13:07.740
I knew for a fact that my ancestors
were not mutineers or pirates.

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:11.330 position:56%
They were proud people who fought an
unjust system and helped free India

00:13:11.330 --> 00:13:14.220
from British, including
Scottish occupation.

00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:19.690
And to at least 2.5 million
people, British citizens with roots

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:25.020
in South Asia, this was the first
significant war of independence.

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:27.770
What a museum should
essentially do is to try

00:13:27.770 --> 00:13:29.930
to make sense of the
world around us.

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:32.170
And lead us back outside,
with a greater

00:13:32.170 --> 00:13:35.600
or empathetic understanding
of the world we live in.

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:39.240
Not just our nation
but our changing world.

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:42.100
It's amazing how personal
paths and new directions

00:13:42.100 --> 00:13:44.410
and world events coincide.

00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:47.940
Soon after I started my
role, the world changed.

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:51.510
We sat round the TV and
watched Twin Towers collapse.

00:13:51.510 --> 00:13:55.250
Soon after a local mosque and a
local synagogue were firebombed.

00:13:55.250 --> 00:13:58.450
Some people were trying to stamp
out difference by attacking places

00:13:58.450 --> 00:14:00.920
of worship at the heart
of community.

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:03.360
Soon after, the curator
of the Islamic collections

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:05.040
and I received a letter
from a gentleman

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:08.720
from the Scottish Muslim community
concerned about what was happening.

00:14:08.720 --> 00:14:12.080
He asked how we in the
museum could respond?

00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:15.560
So we took out the Yellow
Pages and called every place

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:17.770
of worship in [inaudible].

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:22.110
We invited imams, priests, rabbis,
Catholics, Protestants, Muslims,

00:14:22.110 --> 00:14:24.140
Sikhs, Buddhists, and Baha'is.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:28.410 position:56%
Six months later, a single event was
created through a festival format

00:14:28.410 --> 00:14:32.080
to explore faith and belief and
identity in the 21st century.

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:34.660
Where people of faith and
secular traditions stood side

00:14:34.660 --> 00:14:36.720
by side and told their stories.

00:14:36.720 --> 00:14:40.320
Coptic Christians sang songs
of resurrection in Arabic.

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:42.180
Sikhs wore the Scottish Sikh tartan

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:45.220
and performed traditional
bhangra with Scottish bagpipes.

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:46.870
And Jewish Scotts performed music

00:14:46.870 --> 00:14:49.820
that combined Scottish
Celtic and Klezmer tradition.

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:52.700
And in the way that humor
and meaning often coexist,

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:54.510
they named their band
Celtica Shmeltica.

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:57.710
[ Laughter ]

00:14:57.710 --> 00:15:01.680
In that one single event, on
that day, six months after 9/11,

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:04.310
6,000 people of diverse faiths

00:15:04.310 --> 00:15:06.580
and backgrounds decided
to come together.

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:07.890
To stand shoulder to shoulder.

00:15:07.890 --> 00:15:10.910
To use arts, cultures,
and personal storytelling

00:15:10.910 --> 00:15:13.710
as a powerful expression
of community solidarity

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:15.600
at such a time of difficulty.

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:20.170 position:56%
That experience helped me to
realize that if you work in culture,

00:15:20.170 --> 00:15:24.070
in whatever position, you're
a cultural diversity officer.

00:15:24.070 --> 00:15:25.370
It's not a choice.

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:27.740
It's a responsibility.

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:30.990 position:56%
This realization informed [phonetic]
my work over the next few years,

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:33.660
as I was appointed as a
public program curator

00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:36.210
for Glasgow City Museums
and Culture Services.

00:15:36.210 --> 00:15:40.260
Tasked to tackle social justice
issues in a city that has one

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:44.490
of the highest cluster of child
poverty in Europe, 360 gangs,

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:46.590
and where the average
life expectancy for a man

00:15:46.590 --> 00:15:49.470
in the East End is
just 55 years old.

00:15:49.470 --> 00:15:54.290
In a city, within a nation,
riddled with a complex history

00:15:54.290 --> 00:15:56.690
of sectarian and ethnic division.

00:15:56.690 --> 00:16:00.300
It also involved cultural
connections

00:16:00.300 --> 00:16:03.410
through developing storytelling
approaches to societies emerging

00:16:03.410 --> 00:16:07.340
from conflict, with colleagues
from Belfast in Northern Ireland,

00:16:07.340 --> 00:16:10.420
as part of the peace and
reconciliation process.

00:16:10.420 --> 00:16:13.590
I was a first generation
immigrant leading a program

00:16:13.590 --> 00:16:15.570
that addressed a conflict
between Protestants

00:16:15.570 --> 00:16:18.620
and Catholics, white-on-white
violence.

00:16:18.620 --> 00:16:22.110
But as an outsider, as a brown
Asian, English-born Sikh living

00:16:22.110 --> 00:16:25.200
in Scotland of English,
Indian, and African descent.

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:27.770
I was able to use storytelling
and my own story

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:30.640
to communicate the connection
between racism I experienced

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:35.070
as a kid to the sectarian divisions
I was witnessing as an adult.

00:16:35.070 --> 00:16:37.230
Our projects evoked memories.

00:16:37.230 --> 00:16:40.010
I used stories actively collected
from people who were affected

00:16:40.010 --> 00:16:41.890
by the sectarian troubles.

00:16:41.890 --> 00:16:45.170
And when these participants,
including individuals, communities,

00:16:45.170 --> 00:16:48.070
and the wider culture
sector, museums and libraries,

00:16:48.070 --> 00:16:51.830
arts organizations, with support
from political leadership,

00:16:51.830 --> 00:16:53.990
began to invest and
recognize the value

00:16:53.990 --> 00:16:56.830
of the storytelling process
in healing community.

00:16:56.830 --> 00:17:00.510
We were able to collectively
build an effective community model

00:17:00.510 --> 00:17:04.190
that has helped to envision
a new 21st century identity.

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:07.260
Not to ignore the past, but
to reveal it in new ways

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:09.660
and as part of a global community.

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:13.300
These stories were the base of
connections and relationships,

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:16.490
with community leaders,
ex-paramilitary groups,

00:17:16.490 --> 00:17:19.820
territorial gang members,
politicians, police officers,

00:17:19.820 --> 00:17:21.520
people of all different faiths.

00:17:21.520 --> 00:17:23.620 position:56%
To not only collect and tell stories

00:17:23.620 --> 00:17:25.930
but to encourage them
to tell theirs.

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:29.520 position:56%
What might be seen as a mundane
everyday story also offered powerful

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:33.100
ways to explore and thread stories
together, like the Scottish saying.

00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:36.170
There are many threads
of this tartan.

00:17:36.170 --> 00:17:39.870
Enabled important discussions
within a safe environment.

00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:44.380 position:56%
Storytelling offers a search for the
common ground and a place to find

00:17:44.380 --> 00:17:46.300
that important meeting space.

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:50.410
To allow people to seek freedom
by starting to be free in our mind

00:17:50.410 --> 00:17:53.470
and igniting our imagination.

00:17:53.470 --> 00:17:57.350
Envisioning the world without
conflict is hard to do.

00:17:57.350 --> 00:18:00.250
But through story, we can
paint a picture of a world

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:02.120
for ourselves and for others.

00:18:02.120 --> 00:18:03.840
That is possible.

00:18:03.840 --> 00:18:07.290
This is a process that can
take place between two people,

00:18:07.290 --> 00:18:09.800
two communities, or two countries.

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:11.100
It can scale up.

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:13.220
It can scale down.

00:18:13.220 --> 00:18:15.750
But this doesn't always
mean it's easy.

00:18:15.750 --> 00:18:18.250
Using the arts takes
a level of thick skin

00:18:18.250 --> 00:18:19.870
and conviction in our art form.

00:18:19.870 --> 00:18:24.680
The first time I tried to bring in
two rival gangs in a museum space

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:26.260
to share their stories, they broke

00:18:26.260 --> 00:18:29.330
out into an all-out
fight with each other.

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:33.100
But with commitment to building
community we tried again.

00:18:33.100 --> 00:18:36.580
And with specialist support
from partners and city leaders

00:18:36.580 --> 00:18:38.890
that saw the full potential
of storytelling,

00:18:38.890 --> 00:18:41.910
including social workers,
community development officers,

00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:43.300
police officials.

00:18:43.300 --> 00:18:46.120
We developed ways in which
fostered story-based relationships

00:18:46.120 --> 00:18:50.280
that continue to be used to this
day in citywide gang and peace

00:18:50.280 --> 00:18:53.250
and community reconciliation
programs.

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:56.340 position:56%
Models that are now being shared and
storied approaches in building peace

00:18:56.340 --> 00:19:01.010 position:56%
in the Middle East between Arab,
Israeli, Muslim, Christian, and Jew.

00:19:01.010 --> 00:19:03.730
The approach was to see art,
culture, and creativity,

00:19:03.730 --> 00:19:07.300
the process of story-making, not
as a tool to conquer or divide

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:10.860
but instead as a way to heal, to
come together to form community.

00:19:10.860 --> 00:19:12.210
To have a voice.

00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:17.240
To impart wisdom, sometimes ancient
wisdom through the tales we tell.

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:20.090
To follow a belief that in
fact we are all storytellers.

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:23.250
It's just about what type of
storyteller we want to be.

00:19:23.250 --> 00:19:26.060
And that humble approach
led to big things.

00:19:26.060 --> 00:19:29.070
The program we started is now
recognized by UNESCO, the Scottish

00:19:29.070 --> 00:19:32.230
and Northern Ireland
governments, and is now has had

00:19:32.230 --> 00:19:34.480
around 90,000 people
that have participated

00:19:34.480 --> 00:19:36.070
in to tackle bigger
[inaudible] sectarian

00:19:36.070 --> 00:19:38.420 position:56%
and ethnic divisions, gang violence.

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:42.590
It's recognized by her Majesty's
Inspectorate for Education.

00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:45.870
From the time when humans
picked up colored rocks

00:19:45.870 --> 00:19:49.550
and etched visual pictographs
onto cave walls to the day

00:19:49.550 --> 00:19:52.460
when NASA scientists inscribe
the visual human story

00:19:52.460 --> 00:19:56.360
onto a pioneer space probe and
sent it out into the universe,

00:19:56.360 --> 00:19:58.370
humans have told stories.

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:03.770
Storytelling offers us a way to
connect to other ways of life.

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:06.360
To the organic world, with
the forest mountains and seas,

00:20:06.360 --> 00:20:08.080
in which our tales take place.

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:10.850
To the walls in libraries
and corridors of our museums,

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:13.290
our churches, our mosques,
our synagogues,

00:20:13.290 --> 00:20:15.350
and other places of worship.

00:20:15.350 --> 00:20:19.840
As a museum professional living in
Scotland since 2001, my colleagues

00:20:19.840 --> 00:20:23.300
and I, around 2004, were
looking at how we could plan

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:27.730
to mark the 2007 bicentennial
year commemorating the abolition

00:20:27.730 --> 00:20:29.030
of the British slave trade.

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:31.090
It was an important year.

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:33.660
Especially as I was
now living in Glasgow,

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:36.360
also known as the Second
City of the empire.

00:20:36.360 --> 00:20:38.900
But for whom many people did not
realize was built on the back

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:40.930
of transatlantic slavery.

00:20:40.930 --> 00:20:46.990 position:56%
In 2004, I got to hear Lonnie Bunch,
and we invited him to Scotland

00:20:46.990 --> 00:20:49.420
to speak at the UK-wide
museums conference.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:53.700
At that time he was the president
of the Chicago Historical Society

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:56.380
and now, of course, the thinker
behind the new African-American

00:20:56.380 --> 00:20:59.080
Museum being built
on DC's museum mall.

00:20:59.080 --> 00:21:02.260
He said one cannot tackle
racism without grappling

00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:03.560
with the legacies of slavery.

00:21:03.560 --> 00:21:05.280 position:56%
Yet few want to actually discuss it.

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:08.090
I was inspired by his words.

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:11.410
I realized that, as a person
of color and as a product

00:21:11.410 --> 00:21:14.210
of empire that, I was
in a unique position

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:16.470
to facilitate those discussions.

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:19.520
I wanted to take what people
think as two opposing sides

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:23.050
of a conversation and
put them into dialogue.

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:26.000
Lonnie Bunch helped
to spark an idea.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.700
We couldn't literally return these
objects to their rightful owners,

00:21:29.700 --> 00:21:32.350
so we did the next best thing.

00:21:32.350 --> 00:21:36.570
An invitation went out to invite
the members of the African diaspora

00:21:36.570 --> 00:21:39.240
to interpret those objects instead.

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:41.190
Many of those objects
from museum collections

00:21:41.190 --> 00:21:43.970
that had been historically or
been collected and interpret

00:21:43.970 --> 00:21:48.210
through only Western institutional
Eurocentric structures.

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:51.920
An African Voices Exhibition
sought to reinterpret these objects

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:55.910
from first person narratives of
artists and poets and musicians,

00:21:55.910 --> 00:21:58.060
refugees and members of the 30,000

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:00.910
or so African Scottish
diaspora community.

00:22:00.910 --> 00:22:05.380
The project itself was an attempt,
for some of us on the inside,

00:22:05.380 --> 00:22:08.130 position:56%
to relinquish institutional control.

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:10.230 position:56%
By provoking diverse interpretations

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:12.850
of the esthetics of
cultural property.

00:22:12.850 --> 00:22:16.210
This work challenged the idea
of static culture and sought

00:22:16.210 --> 00:22:18.690
to utilize contemporary
traditions drawn from African

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:20.520
and Caribbean folk traditions.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:24.640
Including developing a
Glasgow Haitian voodoo alter,

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:28.300
a Rastafari reggae sound system,
and a commission of new artworks

00:22:28.300 --> 00:22:31.310
for the museum collections on
themes of products of slavery.

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:33.490
By working with artists
of mixed British

00:22:33.490 --> 00:22:36.170
and African-Caribbean heritage.

00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:39.470
[Inaudible] Ford was one of those
artists that was commissioned

00:22:39.470 --> 00:22:41.730
to respond to the yearlong program.

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:44.940
An artist of mixed
Barbadian and British descent,

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:48.900
she used her own body, her own
story, as someone of mixed heritage

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:54.100
to explore herself as an artist,
as a woman, as a legacy of slavery.

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:56.280
Ford's installation The Shadow

00:22:56.280 --> 00:23:00.650
of the Object Fell Upon the Ego
used photography and sculptures

00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:04.630
to explore identity and loss by
enacting the experience of slavery

00:23:04.630 --> 00:23:07.020
as a violent suppression
of identity.

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:09.350
She created a series of
powerful installations

00:23:09.350 --> 00:23:13.330
which included a masked self
portrait wearing a slave mask.

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:15.770
Taken from the museum's
collections originally used

00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:17.650
as a form of punishment.

00:23:17.650 --> 00:23:21.140
Ford described her artwork
as symbolizing the human cost

00:23:21.140 --> 00:23:25.060
of the slave trade and the
prejudice that remains today.

00:23:25.060 --> 00:23:28.770
There was only so far we
could go without breaking

00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:30.810
down the walls of the museum.

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:34.130
But we could utilize the
museum as the object itself.

00:23:34.130 --> 00:23:37.920
As a cultural space to
challenge racism and other forms

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:39.820
of crimes against humanity.

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:41.900
And how we could that
by unpacking how much

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:44.240
of Scotland made its
fortune on the back

00:23:44.240 --> 00:23:47.260
of what many referred
to as tobacco slavery.

00:23:47.260 --> 00:23:49.000
By encouraging us and
others to listen

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.660
for what I believe is the most
important cultural artifact

00:23:51.660 --> 00:23:53.180
for any museum.

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:57.480
People. By incorporating
diverse and uncomfortable stories

00:23:57.480 --> 00:24:00.980
and presenting how much of
Scotland's empire was in fact built

00:24:00.980 --> 00:24:04.030
on the blood and sweat of
people that were once enslaved.

00:24:04.030 --> 00:24:08.120
And how that legacy remains
with us today in various forms.

00:24:08.120 --> 00:24:12.720
As cultural advocates, as
curators, as festival coordinators,

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:14.230
as public administrators.

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:16.750
It's vital that we gather
and assemble people's stories

00:24:16.750 --> 00:24:19.130
to help our audience
listen in new ways.

00:24:19.130 --> 00:24:22.670
As institutions of culture, it's
important that we share history,

00:24:22.670 --> 00:24:27.020
in all its multiplicity, not
shape it into tiny narratives.

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:30.500 position:56%
Harnessing the power of storytelling
to build a better world is not easy,

00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:33.100
but I believe it's an
idea worth cultivating.

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:36.340
We want to empower people all over
the world to tell their stories

00:24:36.340 --> 00:24:38.120
and to hear about other
people's stories.

00:24:38.120 --> 00:24:39.420
To really listen.

00:24:39.420 --> 00:24:40.830
Because when we think about it,

00:24:40.830 --> 00:24:43.790
it's an art where you don't
need special equipment

00:24:43.790 --> 00:24:45.880
or costumes or anything really.

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:49.570
And like Mr George's story had
taught me as a kid in school,

00:24:49.570 --> 00:24:52.780 position:56%
you don't even need a toothbrush or
a cup because the world provides you

00:24:52.780 --> 00:24:55.080
with everything you need.

00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:57.980
In my work and in my life,
I'm incredibly fortunate,

00:24:57.980 --> 00:24:59.790
at the local level
to go into schools

00:24:59.790 --> 00:25:03.340 position:56%
and to help classrooms truly
understand this country's remarkable

00:25:03.340 --> 00:25:04.880
cultural heritage.

00:25:04.880 --> 00:25:07.550
And to work with healthcare
providers, to use story to connect

00:25:07.550 --> 00:25:09.640
with their patients and
to help foster healing.

00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:13.420
On a global level, I get to work
with key partners and collaborators

00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:16.080
to help spread that
storytelling revolution.

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:19.200
Places like the Smithsonian
Institution, NASA,

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:22.180 position:56%
the National Endowment for the
Arts, the Google Cultural Institute,

00:25:22.180 --> 00:25:23.810
